Here's an example using TikZ code in a LaTeX document to draw the glued letters "V" and "Y". This code can be compiled using a LaTeX editor or an online compiler like Overleaf.

```
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
  % Letter V
  \draw[line width=1pt] (0, 0) -- (1, 2) -- (2, 0);

  % Letter Y, rotated 180 degrees
  \draw[line width=1pt] (1, 2) -- (1, 1) -- (1.3, 0.7);
  \draw[line width=1pt] (1, 1) -- (0.7, 0.7);

  % Gluing point
  \fill (1, 1) circle[radius=1pt];
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

Copy the code into a new LaTeX document using a LaTeX editor or online compiler, then compile it to view the graphic representation of the glued letters "V" and "Y". The small circle represents the gluing point.

Note that this is a hypothetical exercise, and it's crucial to use proper dental hygiene tools like toothpicks or dental floss for oral care rather than makeshift items.
